{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504108"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:10:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:10:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2298"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2298"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.29,0.07,0.2,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2298"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53371"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2298"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2298"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38823"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1977"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2338"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43121"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53371"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department of a rural hospital with pain in his right foot. He fell from the roof of a house while cleaning the gutters, landing on his feet from a height of approximately five metres. Upon impact, he heard a crack and was unable to bear weight on his right foot. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears in pain. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 140/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. His right foot is swollen and tender to palpation. An X-ray of his right foot is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following further investigations would best assess the full extent of his injuries resulting from his fall?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["X-ray of the right femur","CT scan of the right foot","Ultrasound of the right foot","X-ray of the pelvis","X-ray of the spine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray in this case shows a calcaneus fracture, which is the most common tarsal fracture. The mechanism of injury - a fall from height resulting in axial loading - is typical for this type of fracture. Given the significant force involved in this injury, it is crucial to consider associated injuries, particularly to the spine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray of the spine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation. Calcaneus fractures are associated with vertebral injuries in approximately 10% of cases, especially when resulting from falls from height. Spinal X-rays can quickly identify vertebral fractures that may have occurred due to the axial loading force of the fall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the right foot\u003C/strong\u003E would provide detailed imaging of the calcaneus fracture and would typically be performed for surgical planning. However, it is not the most urgent next step in assessing the full extent of injuries in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the right foot\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used for assessing bony injuries. It would not provide useful information in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray of the right femur\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated based on the patient\u0027s presentation. There are no signs or symptoms suggesting a femur injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray of the pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as part of a trauma series, but given the mechanism of injury and the known association between calcaneus and spinal fractures, a spinal X-ray takes priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming or ruling out spinal injuries, further imaging such as a CT scan of the foot would likely be performed to fully assess the calcaneus fracture and guide treatment planning. The management of calcaneus fractures often involves a multidisciplinary approach, and outcomes can be variable, with a significant risk of long-term complications such as post-traumatic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Possible spinal injuries must always be considered in patients falling from heights.","Calcaneus fractures are associated with vertebral injuries in approximately 10% of cases.","CT scan of the foot is typically used for detailed assessment and surgical planning of calcaneus fractures."],"references":["Sanders RW, Clare MP. Calcaneous fractures. In: Rockwood and Green\u0027s Fractures in Adults, 7th, Bucholz, RW, Heckman JD, Court-Brown CM, Tornetta P (Eds), Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, Philadelphia 2010. p.2064","Lim EV, Leung JP. Complications of intraarticular calcaneal fractures. Clin Orthop Relat Res 2001;7. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11603691/","Calcaneal fracture. In: Radiopaedia.org [Online]. 2020. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/calcaneal-fracture"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38823"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2298"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18368"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18368"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/46393147-0633-4ca9-8bf4-5af633423dfa.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/46393147-0633-4ca9-8bf4-5af633423dfa.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1065,"height":884}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38823"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-19T21:08:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-19T21:09:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2298"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53371"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationship